    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-05-04T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-05-04T17:00:00-05:00" n="157"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Council/4–2446: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-05-04T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 4, 1946—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2113. <gloss target="#t_Secdel1">Secdel</gloss> 205. Dept wishes to call your
                    attention to Vienna’s 604 Apr 24 repeated to Paris as 72<note n="49"
                        xml:id="d157fn49">Not printed; in it Erhardt recommended certain minimum
                        requirements regarding the release of US-held ships to a proposed
                        Austrian-Soviet steamship company (740.00119 EW/4–2446).</note> and
                    perceives no objections to Erhardt’s recommendations concerning <gloss
                        target="#t_DDSG1">DDSG</gloss> and Danube question. Recommendations,
                    however, should be considered in light of <gloss target="#t_Deptel1"
                        >Deptel</gloss> 982 Apr 26 to Berlin repeated to Paris as 1910.<note n="50"
                        xml:id="d157fn50">Not printed, but for summary of this telegram, see <ref
                            target="#pg_250">p. 250</ref>, last paragraph.</note> If you concur you
                        <pb facs="0272" n="254" xml:id="pg_254"/> may wish to instruct Erhardt to
                    proceed in Vienna on lines he suggests and consider possibility of discussing
                    provisional working agreement concerning Danube as suggested in Vienna’s
                    recommendation.</p>
                <p>Sent to Paris as 2113 <gloss target="#t_Secdel1">Secdel</gloss> 205, repeat to
                    London as 3740 Vienna as 448 and Moscow as 837.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
